rscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 picture of my early days, I must not omit to record those events which led, by insensible steps to my after tale of misery: for when I would account to myself for the birth of that passion \expndtw40 ...\expndtw0  I find it arise, like a mountain river, from ignoble and almost forgotten sources; \expndtw37 ...\expndtw0  it became the torrent which, in its course, has swept away all my hopes and joys."\super 23\nosupersub )}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li7\fi0\ri14\sb264\sa0\sl-259\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 24 or 25 September 1817 PBS again wrote to the publishers (or to the printers [Robert] JVtacdonald & Son\super 24\nosupersub ) and asked "if, particularly during his stay in town, the printer could be urged to expedition. The revi printing is remarkably accurate, & a revise will only be required where there shall happen to be made any considerable corrections of language" \i (SC, \i0 V, 298; see also PBS \i Letters, \i0 I, 558). (For revises that were necessary later, see 28 October 1817 below.)}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li5\fi0\ri12\sb254\sa0\sl-259\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 28 September 1817 MWS from Marlow wrote to PBS in London that "I think you took up my journal of our first travels with you if you did tell me if you have done any thing with it or if you have any prospect\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f2\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af2\loch\f0\cchs0 if you have I will go on instantly with the letters"; in a P.S. she asked "What of Frankenstein?" (MWS \i Letters, \i0 I, 47). (MWS suggests there was neither "prospect" nor contract yet for \i History of a Six Weeks' Tour, \i0 the first half of which [the 1814 "journal"] PBS took to London but the second half of which [the 1816 "letters" from Geneva] had not yet been fair copied\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f2\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af2\loch\f0\cchs0 see 6-17 August 1817 above and 10-12 October and [?14] October 1817 and 6 November 1817 below. MWS's question about \i Frankenstein \i0 might indicate that proofs had not recently been forthcoming.)}\par {\pntext\pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li0\fi0\ri12\sb262\sa0\sl-257\slmult0\tx182 \b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20  5\tab}\pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li0\fi0\ri12\sb262\sa0\sl-257\slmult0\tx182 \f2\fs20{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart5\pnindent182\pnf2}\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 {\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 October 1817 MWS from Marlow wrote to PBS in London that he should "Bring down also your proofs" (MWS \i Letters, \i0 I, 51), possibly referring to the proofs of \i Frankenstein \i0 that he was receiving at this time. (But it is more likely that "your" proofs referred to PBS's epic poem \i Laon and Cythna, \i0 four "sheets" of which he had printed at about this time in order to interest a publisher [see PBS \i Letters, \i0 I, 563].)\super 25}\par {\pntext\pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li0\fi0\ri10\sb259\sa0\sl-257\slmult0\tx182 \b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20  6\tab}\pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li0\fi0\ri10\sb259\sa0\sl-257\slmult0\tx182 \f2\fs20{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart5\pnindent182\pnf2}\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 {\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 October 1817 PBS from London wrote to MWS in Marlow that "I have offered [Claire Clairmont's] book to Lackingtons & to [the publishers] Taylor & Hessey & that they have both declined" (PBS \i Letters, \i0 I, 561). (This now lost "book" may have been a version of the not very good novel that Claire Clairmont began as a story on a "Ideot" back in 1814, but it is equally possible that the book originated in the Geneva ghost-story competition.\super 26 \nosupersub It is worthy of note that almost all other members of the Shelley circle at this time were producing books: not only MWS and PBS's \i History of a Six Weeks\super 3\nosupersub  Tour \i0 [November 1817] and MWS's \i Frankenstein \i0 [January 1818], but also William Godwin's \i Mandeville \i0 [December 1817], PBS's \i Laon and Cythna \i0 [December 1817, withdrawn and republished as \i The Revolt of Islam \i0 in January 1818], Thomas Love Peacock's \i Rhododaphne \i0 [February 1818], and Leigh Hunt's \i Foliage \i0 [February 1818]. All of these works, published within a few months of each other, led to a great flurry of drafts, fair copies, publishing agreements, proofs, revises, authors' copies, advertisements, puffs, and reviews. PBS himself wrote reviews of \i Mandeville, Frankenstein, \i0 and \i Rhododaphne \i0 (see PBS \i Prose, \i0 I, 276-279, 282-288).}\par {\pntext\pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li0\fi0\ri5\sb254\sa0\sl-262\slmult0\tx182 \b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20  7\tab}\pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li0\fi0\ri5\sb254\sa0\sl-262\slmult0\tx182 \f2\fs20{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart5\pnindent182\pnf2}\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 {\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 October 1817 MWS from Marlow wrote to PBS in London and asked him to "Remember my book\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f2\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af2\loch\f0\cchs0 for transcribing" (MWS \i Letters, \expndtw17 1,53),\expndtw0  \i0 the word "transcribing" used to denote fair copying\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f2\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af2\loch\f0\cchs0 in this case the notebook was probably used for \i History of a Six Weeks\super 3\nosupersub  Tour \i0 (see 10-12 October and [?14] October 1817 below).}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li10\fi0\ri2\sb252\sa0\sl-257\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 10-12 October 1817 MWS in her Marlow Journal recorded that she did "write out letters from Geneva" and "transcribe" (MWS \i Journal, \i0 I, 181), indicating that she was preparing a fair copy of the second half of MWS and PBS's \i History of a Six Weeks\super 3\nosupersub  Tour, \i0 which was published on 6 November 1817 (see that date as well as [?14] October 1817 below).}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li12\fi0\ri2\sb259\sa0\sl-259\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 13 October 1817 Entry in Godwin Diary of "Frankenstein, Vol. I" suggests that by this time he read the first volume in proofs (see also 22, 24 November 1817 below).}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li24\fi0\ri0\sb281\sa0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 [?14] October 1817      MWS from Marlow wrote to PBS in London that "I intended\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f2\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af2\loch\f0\cchs0 my best love\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f2\cchs0 \'97\hich\af0\dbch\af2\loch\f0\cchs0 to have sent}\par }